english:
  title: Preface to Seeing Off Envoy Lee Jungbo Upon His Return to Court
  author: Choe Hae
  language: eng
  text: |-
    When Hanlin Scholar Lee Jungbo, having completed his mission to the Provincial Administration of Conquest-East, prepared to return home and came to bid me farewell, I spoke to him thus:

    "The selection of scholars through the civil service examination flourished most during the Tang Dynasty, beginning in the early years of the Changqing era. There was one Kim Yunkyung who first registered as a Silla tributary candidate on the examination list of Du Shili. From that time until the end of the Tianyu era, fifty-eight men passed the Tributary Scholar examination. In the Five Dynasties under Later Liang and Tang, thirty-two more were selected. Excluding some ten from Bohai, all were scholars from the East. When we reach our Goryeo, we too have sent scholars to sit for examinations in Song. During the Chunhua era on Sun He's list appeared Wang Bin and Choe Han. During the Xiangping era on Sun Jin's list appeared Kim Seongjuk. During the Jingyou era on Zhang Tangqing's list appeared Kang Buwon. During the Zhenghe era, in a personal examination, four men including Gwon Juk and Kim Dan were specially granted the highest degree of Upper Residence. From this we can see that the East has never lacked talent from age to age.

    Yet the so-called Tributary Scholar examination required a separate test, with names appended only to the end of the list, never ranking equally with others. The positions granted were mostly menial and redundant, or men were simply sent back home. Only in the sacred Yuan dynasty has there been equal regard for all. In elevating the worthy, they observe no rigid method. Thus scholars from the East now participate together with the finest talents of the Central Plain, their names inscribed on the golden register—six men already. Though Jungbo came later, he has been selected for the highest examination and appointed to an office in the imperial palace, with honors extending to both parents, who have received imperial favor. He bears the imperial edict with glory to his homeland, pays respects to his mother, makes offerings at ancestral graves—bringing honor to both the living and the departed. Having achieved his aspirations and returned to his native place, he is not alone in his glory, as even the ancient Changjing did not monopolize the praise of Shu and Yue.

    Our ancestor, Minister Munchang Choe Chiwon, journeyed westward at the age of twelve and ascended to the examination list at eighteen in the fifteenth year of Xiantong. He served as magistrate of Zhongshan and assisted General Gao, Minister of the Right, in his headquarters. His office rose to that of Censor and Inner Court Official. At twenty-eight he received a mission and returned to his homeland. People of the region have transmitted his story as a beautiful tale to this very day. This was during the final years of Tang, when warfare blazed across all lands. Yet our Minister, with the lonely fate of a sojourner, sustained himself at the regional commands. Though he received official rank, his position was not substantive. When he returned to the East, the country too was in great turmoil. The roads became impassable, and he never completed his mission. Reflecting on his lifetime: his diligence was considerable, yet the glory was hardly worth mentioning. How different from our Jungbo! He encounters this age of luminous peace, establishes himself near the throne, and at the height of his vigor, his aspirations grow ever more humble. His future prospects cannot be easily measured. The honor and glory of family and nation will not end here alone. Surely we shall see wealth and honor embrace him, his name and fame spread throughout the realm, and the Hall of Daytime Splendor erected grandly in the Eastern Korean lands. I cannot foresee how posterity will view Jungbo compared to the ancients of the East.

    I recall further that in the first year of Zhizhi, I myself, through mere fortune, traveled with the roster of candidates. That year the number of examination candidates had not yet reached full quota, and only forty-three ascended the Dragon List. I was fortunate to be the twenty-first. I received appointment as Magistrate's Deputy and took office for only a few months before illness forced me to retire. Now for thirteen years I have dwelt in quiet seclusion at the village's edge. My youthful ambitions have waned day by day, and I have no more strength to soar aloft.

    Seeing Jungbo now, I understand all the more that I have merely abandoned myself and accomplished nothing. How can I face the favor of this sacred dynasty? Jungbo, I urge you further: do not let the filling of one final basket prevent the completion of the great nine-fathom height. My bond with Jungbo runs deep. I admire his conduct and, humbled by my own inadequacy, I encourage his further striving.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The Hall of Daytime Splendor (晝錦堂) is a reference to a traditional structure built by successful officials upon their return home, symbolizing the display of honors and achievements to their native place.
  - key: ''
    value: The nine-fathom height is a metaphor for great achievement, derived from classical poetry imagery suggesting that even the smallest final effort completes a magnificent structure.
  - key: ''
    value: Kim Yunkyung marks the beginning of documented East Asian participation in Chinese civil service examinations, representing the formal integration of tributary scholars into the imperial system.
